// workload.kara â€” Three driver functions and the `process_request`
// aggregator whose body is the slice's load-bearing code.
//
// `process_request` has exactly three top-level call statements with no
// `let` bindings. Slice 2's auto-par codegen picks this shape up because:
//   1. The analyzer (concurrency.rs) sees three disjoint `writes(R_i)`
//      effects (no conflict edges â†’ groupable).
//   2. The granularity heuristic classifies the group non-trivial (the
//      `writes` effects are non-empty).
//   3. The `group_defines_binding_used_outside` gate doesn't fire (no
//      bindings are introduced).
// `compile_function_body` therefore emits a single `karac_par_run` call
// that fans out the three `record_*` calls across the runtime's worker
// pool.
//
// Why not call `MetricsA.record(WORK)` here? In v1 the
// `with_provider[R](instance, || { ... })` mechanism in db_pipeline
// has GAP-N (resource-method dispatch syntax under-specified) â€” the
// codegen does not yet wire the trait-method call inside a provider
// scope to the concrete impl, so a `MetricsA.record(...)` call is a
// no-op at runtime. To keep the wall-clock benchmark meaningful we
// inline the busy-compute kernel directly into each driver. The
// effect resources `MetricsA / B / C` remain declared (in
// resources.kara) and the driver functions remain effect-annotated
// `writes(MetricsA / B / C)` â€” that is what the auto-par analyzer
// keys off, and it is unaffected by the provider GAP. Once GAP-N
// closes, the `record_*` bodies can swap to `MetricsA.record(WORK)`
// without touching the surrounding shape.
//
// Demo-shape gap: the canonical Parallax demo (fan-out + join) is *not*
// what this workload models. Joining results from parallel branches
// requires per-branch return slots in `karac_par_run`'s ABI â€” the
// open `phase-7-codegen.md:182` "Par codegen: return values" entry.
// Slice 6 ships effect-only fan-out as the v1 measurement workload.

import resources.{MetricsA, MetricsB, MetricsC};

// Per-iteration loop count for the busy-compute kernel. ~50M iterations
// is enough to dominate thread-spawn / RC-fallback overhead on the
// auto-par branch on a typical laptop, so the wall-clock benchmark
// sees signal. Hoisting to a `pub const` lets benchmark sweeps tune a
// single source-of-truth without editing every driver.
pub const WORK: i64 = 50000000;

// Busy-compute kernel inlined into each driver. The running sum is
// published via a printout so the optimizer cannot strip the loop
// body. Each driver carries a distinct `writes(R_i)` effect on
// disjoint resources â€” the analyzer's groupability key.
//
// The kernel uses only `+` (no `%`/`/`) intentionally: the
// `__builtin_div_rem` builtin carries an inferred `panics` effect
// (div-by-zero), and `panics + panics` is a self-conflict in the
// concurrency analyzer (correctly modeling that concurrent panic
// aggregation is undefined). Using `%` for modular reduction would
// cause the three drivers to inherit `panics` and refuse to group,
// short-circuiting the whole demo. `i64` overflow is *outside* the
// effect system's scope per `effectchecker.rs:380` â€” overflow traps
// are runtime concerns, not effect-system concerns. The sum
// `0+1+...+50M` â‰ˆ 1.25e15 fits in `i64::MAX` (â‰ˆ9.2e18) with three
// orders of magnitude of headroom, so the loop is overflow-safe.

fn record_a() with writes(MetricsA) {
    let mut sum: i64 = 0;
    let mut i: i64 = 0;
    while i < WORK {
        sum = sum + i;
        i = i + 1;
    }
    println(sum);
}

fn record_b() with writes(MetricsB) {
    let mut sum: i64 = 0;
    let mut i: i64 = 0;
    while i < WORK {
        sum = sum + i;
        i = i + 1;
    }
    println(sum);
}

fn record_c() with writes(MetricsC) {
    let mut sum: i64 = 0;
    let mut i: i64 = 0;
    while i < WORK {
        sum = sum + i;
        i = i + 1;
    }
    println(sum);
}

// The aggregator. Three top-level call statements, no return value.
// This is *exactly* the shape slice 2's `compile_function_body`
// dispatches through `emit_par_run`. All three `record_*` calls run
// concurrently when `KARAC_AUTO_PAR != 0` (default); with
// `KARAC_AUTO_PAR=0` the slice 6 codegen gate falls back to plain
// sequential `compile_block`, providing the side-by-side benchmark
// baseline.
pub fn process_request() with writes(MetricsA) writes(MetricsB) writes(MetricsC) {
    record_a();
    record_b();
    record_c();
}
